  "prompt": "What does sensitivity, frequency response, maximum power input, impedance, harmonic distortion, etc., indicate about a particular headphone?",
  "response": "Here's what different headphone specifications indicate:\n\n1. Sensitivity\n- Measures how loud headphones get with a given amount of electrical input\n- Higher sensitivity means louder sound at the same power level\n- Typically measured in decibels per milliwatt (dB/mW)\n- Higher is generally better for driving headphones with lower-powered devices\n\n2. Frequency Response\n- Shows the range of audio frequencies the headphones can reproduce\n- Typically measured from lowest (bass) to highest (treble) frequencies\n- Wider range indicates more complete sound reproduction\n- Measured in Hertz (Hz), e.g., 20Hz-20kHz\n\n3. Maximum Power Input\n- Maximum electrical power headphones can handle without damage\n- Indicates durability and potential volume capabilities\n- Measured in watts or milliwatts\n- Higher values suggest more robust design\n\n4. Impedance\n- Electrical resistance of headphone drivers\n- Affects how much power is needed to drive the headphones\n- Measured in ohms (\u03a9)\n- Low impedance (< 50\u03a9) works well with portable devices\n- High impedance (> 100\u03a9) requires more powerful amplification\n\n5. Harmonic Distortion\n- Measure of sound signal accuracy\n- Lower percentages indicate cleaner, more accurate sound reproduction\n- Typically expressed as Total Harmonic Distortion (THD)\n\nThese specifications help evaluate headphone performance and compatibility.",
